My Meme

This meme is inspired by the expanding brain series of images, where each level, each subsequent image is a smarter idea than the previous one. I thought it would be funny and get meta about the project!

library(magick)
# this code makes a really funny meme. The block below loads in images
brain1 <- image_read('brain1.jfif') #281 x 179 
brain2 <- image_read('brain2.jfif') #291 x 173
brain3 <- image_read('brain3.jfif') #285 x 177
cat <- image_read('cat.jpg') # 3024 x 4032

# these blocks create each of the four horizontal portions of the meme
blank1 <- image_blank(width = 286, height = 179, color = '#FFFFFF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'making a unfunny meme for stats220', 
                 gravity = 'center')
slide1 <- image_append(c(blank1, image_scale(brain1, 286)))

blank2 <- image_blank(width = 286, height = 173, color = '#FFFFFF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'making a mildly funny meme for stats220', 
                 gravity = 'center')
slide2 <- image_append(c(blank2, image_scale(brain2, 286)))

blank3 <- image_blank(width = 286, height = 177, color = '#FFFFFF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'making a meme that references cats for stats 220',
                 gravity = 'center')
slide3 <- image_append(c(blank3, image_scale(brain3, 286)))

blank4 <- image_blank(width = 286, height = 177, color = '#FFFFFF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'miaow (thanks to my flatmates cat trixie)', 
                 gravity = 'center')
# this specifically changes the size of trixie, who is a very large image
fixed_cat <- image_scale(cat, 286) %>%
  image_crop('286x177', gravity = 'north')
slide4 <- image_append(c(blank4, fixed_cat))

# this combines all the slides for the meme
image_append(c(slide1, slide2, slide3, slide4), stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_write('my_meme.png')

My Animated GIF

My gif is inspired by a sunset, and uses the calm fade of a sunset to be nice and relaxing.

library(magick)
# the code below produces a sunset animated gif
# This first block produces each of the seven slides for the gif
slide1 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#692DA5') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx', size = 40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#262626', font = 'Candara')

slide2 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#B366FF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx..', size =40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#4D4D4D',font = 'Candara')

slide3 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#DF80FF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx...', size = 40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#4D4D4D',font = 'Candara')

slide4 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#FFB3FF') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx...', size = 40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#4D4D4D',font = 'Candara') 

slide5 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#FFB3B3') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx...', size = 40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#4D4D4D',font = 'Candara')

slide6 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#FFAA80') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx...', size = 40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#4D4D4D',font = 'Candara')

slide7 <- image_blank(width = 500, height = 500, color = '#FF944D') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'relaxxx...', size = 40, gravity = 'NorthEast',
                 color = '#4D4D4D',font = 'Candara')

# this section animates and morphs the frames, then saves the gif
frames <- c(slide1, slide2, slide3, slide4, slide5, slide6, slide7)
animation <-image_morph(frames)%>%
  image_animate(fps = 20)
image_write(animation, 'my_animation.gif')
